      "Creating a QR code is easy. Creating one that is actually useful is where most people get stuck. Many users paste a link into a random generator, download the image, and assume the job is done. Later they discover the code is too small to scan, placed badly inside a design, or linked to the wrong destination. If you use QR codes for menus, flyers, support pages, payments, product packaging, business cards, or event check-ins, those details matter far more than the act of generation itself.",
      "This guide is designed for that practical reality. It explains how to create a QR code for free, what to link it to, how to test it, and where to place it so people actually use it. If you want to generate one immediately, start with the [QR Code Generator](/tools/qr-code-generator). If you also need to verify an existing code from an image or screenshot, the [QR Code Scanner](/tools/qr-code-scanner) is useful as a follow-up step.",
      "## What a QR Code Actually Does",
      "A QR code is simply a visual way of storing machine-readable information. Most often, that information is a URL, but it can also be plain text, contact details, event links, payment instructions, or Wi-Fi setup information. The practical advantage is speed. Instead of making a user type a long address, search for a page manually, or save a number from a printed brochure, a phone camera can open the destination almost instantly.",
      "That speed makes QR codes especially useful in environments where attention is limited. People at a shop counter, restaurant table, trade-show booth, campus noticeboard, or product shelf usually do not want to type anything if they can avoid it. A good QR code removes friction from the next action. That might be browsing a menu, filling a lead form, opening installation instructions, joining a WhatsApp group, or downloading a brochure. In other words, the QR code is not the goal. The next step is.",
      "## When You Should Use a QR Code",
