      "The strongest use cases usually have one clear action. Menus, registrations, support docs, reviews, catalog pages, payment notes, and vCards work well because they offer a direct and obvious next step. Weak use cases usually point to something vague, outdated, or overloaded with options. If the landing page itself is confusing, the QR code will not rescue it. That is why you should think about the destination before you think about the design.",
      "## How to Create a QR Code for Free",
      "The simplest workflow is also the best one for most users. First, choose the exact destination. If you are linking to a website, make sure the URL is live, mobile-friendly, and preferably short enough to manage. Second, paste that destination into a reliable browser-based generator such as the [QR Code Generator](/tools/qr-code-generator). Third, create the code and preview it before download. Fourth, test it on at least one phone before placing it into a design or sending it to print. This entire process takes minutes, but it prevents most of the common errors people make.",
      "If your use case involves text instead of a link, the same process applies. The output is still a static QR code, but the destination becomes a readable text payload rather than a web page. This can be useful for short instructions, product IDs, coupon codes, or simple messages. However, for long bodies of text, a landing page is usually better because it gives you more control and makes scanning easier for the end user.",
      "## Best Practices Before You Download",
      "A QR code should be treated like any other user-facing asset. Test it in realistic conditions. Scan it from the actual phone model you expect users to have. If it will appear on paper, print a rough sample first. If it will appear on packaging, view it at the actual size. Check whether the destination opens fast and whether the page is usable on mobile. Many QR campaigns fail not because the code is broken, but because the landing page is slow, cluttered, or not optimized for the context in which it is being scanned.",
      "Size and contrast matter more than decoration. A dark code on a light background is the safest choice. Tiny codes are risky, especially on glossy print or when viewed from a distance. Over-designed QR graphics may look attractive in a mockup but reduce real-world scan reliability. If the code is tied to a business workflow, clarity should always beat novelty. In most cases, a clean black-and-white PNG with enough surrounding space performs better than a heavily stylized version.",
      "## Common Mistakes That Reduce Scans",
      "The first common mistake is linking to the wrong thing. Users sometimes send people to a homepage when the real goal is a contact page, booking form, menu, or support article. The second mistake is poor placement. If a QR code is tucked into a crowded poster corner or placed where glare hits it, users may ignore it or struggle to scan it. The third mistake is lack of instruction. A short line such as 'Scan to view menu' or 'Scan to register' can improve scan intent because it explains the benefit immediately.",
      "Another mistake is skipping the verification step. Before publishing, use a scanner to confirm the output works from the final asset, not just from the raw generator preview. The [QR Code Scanner](/tools/qr-code-scanner) helps if you want to inspect a saved design, screenshot, or proof image before approval. That extra check is especially helpful for agencies, print shops, and internal marketing teams that review assets before distribution.",
      "## Where Free QR Codes Work Best",
